0.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
0.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
0.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
0.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
0.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 6652 seconds.

3.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
3.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
3.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
3.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
3.Plugin Output: Port 25/tcp was found to be open

15.Synopsis: The remote service implements TCP timestamps.
15.Description:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323.  A
side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote host can
sometimes be computed.

16.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
16.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
16.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

The device responded to an SSDP M-SEARCH request with the following locations :

    http://192.168.12.1:49152/.cnb-ipcam.xml

And advertises these unique service names :

    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B99::upnp:rootdevice
    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B99::urn:schemas-upnp-org:device:Basic:1
    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B99::urn:cnbtec-com:service:BasicService:1

17.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
17.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
17.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
17.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

19.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
19.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
19.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
19.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
19.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.

29.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
29.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
29.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
29.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

32.Name: Open Port Re-check
32.Synopsis: Previously open ports are now closed.
32.Description:
One of several ports that were previously open are now closed or
unresponsive.

There are several possible reasons for this :

  - The scan may have caused a service to freeze or stop
    running.

  - An administrator may have stopped a particular service
    during the scanning process.

This might be an availability problem related to the following :

  - A network outage has been experienced during the scan,
    and the remote network cannot be reached anymore by the
    scanner.

  - This scanner may has been blacklisted by the system
    administrator or by an automatic intrusion detection /
    prevention system that detected the scan.

  - The remote host is now down, either because a user
    turned it off during the scan or because a select denial
    of service was effective.

In any case, the audit of the remote host might be incomplete and may
need to be done again.

44.Description:

supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides

45.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
45.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
45.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
45.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

46.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
46.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
46.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
46.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

97.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
97.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
97.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
97.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

104.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.

The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
104.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

channel.

passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.

121.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
121.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
121.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
121.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2

130.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
130.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
130.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
130.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

132.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
132.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
132.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
132.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
193.Solution:

timestamp replies (14).

267.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
267.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
267.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
267.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

269.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
269.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
269.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
269.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

271.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
271.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
271.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
271.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

280.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
280.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
280.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
280.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

282.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
282.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
282.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
282.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
282.Plugin Output:
The ICMP timestamps seem to be in little endian format (not in network format)
The difference between the local and remote clocks is 15497 seconds.

284.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
284.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

286.Name: TFTP Daemon Detection
286.Synopsis: A TFTP server is listening on the remote port.
286.Description:
The remote host is running a TFTP (Trivial File Transfer Protocol)

392.Name: Open Port Re-check
392.Synopsis: Previously open ports are now closed.
392.Description:
One of several ports that were previously open are now closed or
unresponsive.

There are several possible reasons for this :

  - The scan may have caused a service to freeze or stop
    running.

  - An administrator may have stopped a particular service
    during the scanning process.

This might be an availability problem related to the following :

  - A network outage has been experienced during the scan,
    and the remote network cannot be reached anymore by the
    scanner.

  - This scanner may has been blacklisted by the system
    administrator or by an automatic intrusion detection /
    prevention system that detected the scan.

  - The remote host is now down, either because a user
    turned it off during the scan or because a select denial
    of service was effective.

In any case, the audit of the remote host might be incomplete and may
need to be done again.
392.Plugin Output: Port 5000 was detected as being open but is now closed

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
405.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

406.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
406.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
406.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
406.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

408.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
408.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
408.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
408.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

417.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
417.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.

mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.

418.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
418.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
418.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
418.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
418.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 4647 seconds.

430.Name: TCP/IP Timestamps Supported
430.Synopsis: The remote service implements TCP timestamps.
430.Description:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323.  A
side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote host can
sometimes be computed.

431.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
431.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
431.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B81::urn:schemas-upnp-org:device:Basic:1
    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B81::urn:cnbtec-com:service:BasicService:1

432.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
432.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
432.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
432.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

433.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
433.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
433.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
433.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

435.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
435.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
435.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
435.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

444.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
444.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
444.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
444.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

455.Name: MS11-030: Vulnerability in DNS Resolution Could Allow Remote Code Execution (2509553) (remote check)
455.Synopsis:
Arbitrary code can be executed on the remote host through the
installed Windows DNS client.
455.Description:
A flaw in the way the installed Windows DNS client processes Link-
local Multicast Name Resolution (LLMNR) queries can be exploited to
execute arbitrary code in the context of the NetworkService account.

Note that Windows XP and 2003 do not support LLMNR and successful
exploitation on those platforms requires local access and the ability
to run a special application. On Windows Vista, 2008, 7, and 2008 R2,
however, the issue can be exploited remotely.
455.Solution:
Microsoft has released a set of patches for Windows XP, 2003, Vista,
2008, 7, and 2008 R2.

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

472.Name: Open Port Re-check
472.Synopsis: Previously open ports are now closed.
472.Description:
One of several ports that were previously open are now closed or
unresponsive.

There are several possible reasons for this :

  - The scan may have caused a service to freeze or stop
    running.

  - An administrator may have stopped a particular service
    during the scanning process.

This might be an availability problem related to the following :

  - A network outage has been experienced during the scan,
    and the remote network cannot be reached anymore by the
    scanner.

  - This scanner may has been blacklisted by the system
    administrator or by an automatic intrusion detection /
    prevention system that detected the scan.

  - The remote host is now down, either because a user
    turned it off during the scan or because a select denial
    of service was effective.

In any case, the audit of the remote host might be incomplete and may
need to be done again.

490.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
490.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
490.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
490.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

492.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
492.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
492.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
492.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

496.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
496.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
496.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
496.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
496.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: TCP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

513.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
513.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
513.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
513.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

  - Advertised services :

      Port number       : 80

514.Name: Web Site Client Access Policy File Detection
514.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'clientaccesspolicy.xml' file.
514.Description:
The remote web server contains a client access policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Microsoft Silverlight to allow access to
services that reside outside the exact web domain from which a
Silverlight control originated.
514.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery or other attacks against the web server.

516.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
516.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
516.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
516.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

quick even against a firewalled target.

firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote host can
sometimes be computed.

530.Name: Web Site Cross-Domain Policy File Detection
530.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'crossdomain.xml' file.
530.Description:
The remote web server contains a cross-domain policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Adobe's Flash Player to allow access to data
that resides outside the exact web domain from which a Flash movie
file originated.
530.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery and cross-site scripting attacks against the web
server.

host using the following URL :

531.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
531.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
531.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

532.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
532.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
532.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
532.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

533.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
533.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
533.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
533.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

535.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
535.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
535.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
535.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

560.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
560.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
560.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

    are allowed on :

585.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
585.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
585.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
585.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

587.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
587.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
587.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
587.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
587.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

596.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
596.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
596.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
596.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.
596.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to extract the following information :

  - mDNS hostname       : XNET-001E81501B98.local.

  - Advertised services :
    o Service name      : XNET-001E81501B98._http._tcp.local.
      Port number       : 80

597.Name: Web Site Client Access Policy File Detection
597.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'clientaccesspolicy.xml' file.
597.Description:
The remote web server contains a client access policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Microsoft Silverlight to allow access to
services that reside outside the exact web domain from which a
Silverlight control originated.
597.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery or other attacks against the web server.
597.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to obtain a client access policy file from the
remote host at the following URL :

  GET /clientaccesspolicy.xml HTTP/1.0
Accept-Charset: iso-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.9,*;q=0.1
Accept-Language: en
Connection: Close
User-Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0)
Pragma: no-cache
Accept: image/gif, image/x-xbitmap, image/jpeg, image/pjpeg, image/png, */*

598.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
598.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
598.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
598.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
598.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 9938 seconds.

server.

An RTSP (Real Time Streaming Protocol) server is listening on the
remote port.

multimedia presentation protocol, which is used to stream videos and
audio files over an IP network. 

It is usually possible to obtain the list of capabilities and the
server name of the remote RTSP server by sending an OPTIONS request.

603.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
603.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
603.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
603.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.
603.Plugin Output: Port 25/tcp was found to be open

613.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

614.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
614.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
614.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
614.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

615.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
615.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
615.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
615.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

617.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
617.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
617.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
617.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2

642.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
642.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
642.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
642.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.

Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
665.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

666.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
666.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
666.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
666.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

668.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
668.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
668.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
668.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

677.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
677.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.

mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
677.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

678.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
678.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
678.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
678.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
678.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 7692 seconds.

691.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

692.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
692.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
692.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
692.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

694.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
694.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
694.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
694.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

696.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
696.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
696.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
696.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
696.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
705.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.
705.Plugin Output:

  - mDNS hostname       : XNET-001E81501B7C.local.

  - Advertised services :
    o Service name      : XNET-001E81501B7C._http._tcp.local.
      Port number       : 80

706.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
706.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
706.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
706.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
706.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 8694 seconds.

709.Description:

quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.

719.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
719.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
719.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B95::urn:schemas-upnp-org:device:Basic:1
    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B95::urn:cnbtec-com:service:BasicService:1

720.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
720.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
720.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
720.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

available from the scan.

722.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
722.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
722.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
722.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

724.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
724.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
724.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
724.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
724.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.

734.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
734.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
734.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
734.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

748.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
748.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
748.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
748.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

750.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
750.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
750.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
750.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

761.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
761.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
761.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
761.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

762.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
762.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
762.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
762.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
762.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 2344 seconds.

776.Name: Web Site Cross-Domain Policy File Detection
776.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'crossdomain.xml' file.

simple XML file used by Adobe's Flash Player to allow access to data
that resides outside the exact web domain from which a Flash movie
file originated.
776.Solution:

especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-

server.

supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides

for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

778.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
778.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
778.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
778.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

780.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
780.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
780.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
780.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

791.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
791.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
791.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
791.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.
