792.Name: Web Site Client Access Policy File Detection
792.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'clientaccesspolicy.xml' file.
792.Description:
The remote web server contains a client access policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Microsoft Silverlight to allow access to
services that reside outside the exact web domain from which a
Silverlight control originated.
792.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery or other attacks against the web server.

Pragma: no-cache

793.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
793.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
793.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
793.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

806.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it

for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

807.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
807.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
807.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
807.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

808.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
808.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
808.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
808.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

819.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
819.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
819.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
819.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.
819.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to extract the following information :

  - mDNS hostname       : XNET-001E81501B91.local.

  - Advertised services :
    o Service name      : XNET-001E81501B91._http._tcp.local.
      Port number       : 80

820.Name: Web Site Client Access Policy File Detection
820.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'clientaccesspolicy.xml' file.
820.Description:
The remote web server contains a client access policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Microsoft Silverlight to allow access to
services that reside outside the exact web domain from which a
Silverlight control originated.
820.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery or other attacks against the web server.
820.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to obtain a client access policy file from the
remote host at the following URL :

  GET /clientaccesspolicy.xml HTTP/1.0
Accept-Charset: iso-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.9,*;q=0.1
Accept-Language: en
Connection: Close
User-Agent: Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0)
Pragma: no-cache
Accept: image/gif, image/x-xbitmap, image/jpeg, image/pjpeg, image/png, */*

821.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
821.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
821.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
821.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
821.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 5414 seconds.

822.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server, a remote terminal
server.
822.Solution: Disable this service if you do not use it.

824.Name: Nessus SYN scanner
824.Synopsis: It is possible to determine which TCP ports are open.
824.Description:
This plugin is a SYN 'half-open' port scanner.  It shall be reasonably
quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
824.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.

833.Name: TCP/IP Timestamps Supported
833.Synopsis: The remote service implements TCP timestamps.
833.Description:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323.  A
side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote host can
sometimes be computed.

834.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
834.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
834.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

835.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
835.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
835.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
835.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

836.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
836.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
836.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
836.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

838.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
838.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
838.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
838.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

847.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
847.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
847.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
847.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.
847.Plugin Output:
Nessus was able to extract the following information :

  - mDNS hostname       : XNET-001E81501B9F.local.

  - Advertised services :
    o Service name      : XNET-001E81501B9F._http._tcp.local.
      Port number       : 80

848.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
848.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
848.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
848.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
848.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 2093 seconds.

849.Name: Telnet Server Detection
849.Synopsis: A Telnet server is listening on the remote port.
849.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server, a remote terminal
server.
849.Solution: Disable this service if you do not use it.

851.Description:

quick even against a firewalled target. 

Note that SYN scans are less intrusive than TCP (full connect) scans
against broken services, but they might cause problems for less robust
firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if
the network is loaded.
851.Solution: Protect your target with an IP filter.

860.Synopsis: The remote service implements TCP timestamps.
860.Description:
The remote host implements TCP timestamps, as defined by RFC1323.  A
side effect of this feature is that the uptime of the remote host can
sometimes be computed.

861.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
861.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
861.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

    uuid:Upnp-BasicDevice-1_0-001E81501B8E::urn:cnbtec-com:service:BasicService:1

862.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
862.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
862.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
862.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

864.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
864.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
864.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
864.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

866.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
866.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
866.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
866.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
866.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.

876.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
876.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
876.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
876.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

891.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
891.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
891.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
891.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

892.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
892.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
892.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
892.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
899.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
899.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: TCP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

911.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
911.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
911.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.

912.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
912.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
912.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
912.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

926.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
926.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
926.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
926.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

927.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
927.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
927.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
927.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

929.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
929.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
929.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
929.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
929.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP

(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
935.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

938.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
938.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
938.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
938.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

      Port number       : 80

939.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
939.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
939.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
939.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
939.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 3652 seconds.

951.Name: Universal Plug and Play (UPnP) Protocol Detection
951.Description:
The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.
951.Solution: Filter access to this port if desired.

952.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
952.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
952.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
952.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

959.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
959.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
959.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
959.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running.

network segment as Nessus.

964.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
964.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
964.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
964.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

979.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'crossdomain.xml' file.

simple XML file used by Adobe's Flash Player to allow access to data
that resides outside the exact web domain from which a Flash movie
file originated.

especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery and cross-site scripting attacks against the web
server.

982.Name: Unencrypted Telnet Server
982.Synopsis: The remote Telnet server transmits traffic in cleartext.
982.Description:
The remote host is running a Telnet server over an unencrypted
channel.

Using Telnet over an unencrypted channel is not recommended as logins,
passwords, and commands are transferred in cleartext. This allows a 
remote, man-in-the-middle attacker to eavesdrop on a Telnet session to
obtain credentials or other sensitive information and to modify
traffic exchanged between a client and server.

SSH is preferred over Telnet since it protects credentials from
eavesdropping and can tunnel additional data streams such as an X11
session.
982.Solution: Disable the Telnet service and use SSH instead.

983.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
983.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
983.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
983.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

987.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
987.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
987.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)

1002.Name: mDNS Detection (Local Network)
1002.Synopsis: It is possible to obtain information about the remote host.
1002.Description:
The remote service understands the Bonjour (also known as ZeroConf or
mDNS) protocol, which allows anyone to uncover information from the
remote host such as its operating system type and exact version, its
hostname, and the list of services it is running. 

This plugin attempts to discover mDNS used by hosts residing on the same
network segment as Nessus.
1002.Solution: Filter incoming traffic to UDP port 5353, if desired.

1003.Name: Web Site Client Access Policy File Detection
1003.Synopsis: The remote web server contains a 'clientaccesspolicy.xml' file.
1003.Description:
The remote web server contains a client access policy file.  This is a
simple XML file used by Microsoft Silverlight to allow access to
services that reside outside the exact web domain from which a
Silverlight control originated.
1003.Solution:
Review the contents of the policy file carefully.  Improper policies,
especially an unrestricted one with just '*', could allow for cross-
site request forgery or other attacks against the web server.

1005.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1005.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1005.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1005.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

1022.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1022.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1022.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1022.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.

Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2

1047.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1047.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1047.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1047.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1047.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1072.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1072.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1072.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1072.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1072.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1080.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.

The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1080.Solution:

timestamp replies (14).

1122.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1122.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1122.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1122.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1122.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1130.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1130.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1130.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

1197.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1197.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1197.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1197.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1197.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1205.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1205.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1205.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1205.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1205.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -85 seconds.

1229.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1229.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1229.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1229.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).

1241.Description:

supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides
automatic configuration and device discovery. It is primarily intended
for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

1242.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
1242.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
1242.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
1242.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

1244.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
1244.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
1244.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1244.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
1244.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1250.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

1251.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
1251.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
1251.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1251.Solution:

third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of

1297.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1297.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1297.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1297.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1297.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1305.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1305.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1305.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1305.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1305.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -120 seconds.

1330.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1330.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1330.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1330.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1330.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is -8295 seconds.

firewalls and also leave unclosed connections on the remote target, if

1347.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1347.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1347.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1347.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1347.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

1372.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1372.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1372.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1372.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1372.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

1422.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1422.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1422.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1422.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1422.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

1495.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1495.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1495.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1495.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1495.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

IP forwarding.
1516.Solution:

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

1518.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
1518.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
1518.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1518.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
1518.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

1530.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1530.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1530.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1530.Solution:

timestamp replies (14).

1547.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1547.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1547.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1547.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1547.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

authentication protocols.

the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

1597.Name: MiniUPnP < 1.4 Multiple Vulnerabilities
1597.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host has multiple
vulnerabilities.
1597.Description:
According to its banner, the version of MiniUPnP running on the remote
host is prior to 1.4. It is, therefore, affected by the following
vulnerabilities :

  - An out-of-bounds read error exists in the
    ProcessSSDPRequest() function in file minissdp.c that
    allows an unauthenticated, remote attacker to cause a
    denial of service condition via a specially crafted
    M-SEARCH request. (CVE-2013-0229)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    ExecuteSoapAction() function in the SOAPAction handler,
    due to improper validation of user-supplied input. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    long quoted method, to cause a denial of service
    condition or the execution of arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2013-0230)
1597.Solution: Upgrade to MiniUPnP version 1.4 or later.
1597.Plugin Output:
Server banner : MandrivaLinux/2009.0 UPnP/1.0 MiniUPnPd/1.2
  Installed version : 1.2
  Fixed version : 1.4

attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.

timestamp replies (14).

1618.Name: HTTP Methods Allowed (per directory)
1618.Synopsis:
This plugin determines which HTTP methods are allowed on various CGI
directories.
1618.Description:
By calling the OPTIONS method, it is possible to determine which HTTP
methods are allowed on each directory.

The following HTTP methods are considered insecure:
  PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, TRACE, HEAD

Many frameworks and languages treat 'HEAD' as a 'GET' request, albeit
one without any body in the response. If a security constraint was
set on 'GET' requests such that only 'authenticatedUsers' could
access GET requests for a particular servlet or resource, it would be
bypassed for the 'HEAD' version. This allowed unauthorized blind
submission of any privileged GET request.

As this list may be incomplete, the plugin also tests - if 'Thorough
tests' are enabled or 'Enable web applications tests' is set to 'yes'
in the scan policy - various known HTTP methods on each directory and
considers them as unsupported if it receives a response code of 400,
403, 405, or 501.

Note that the plugin output is only informational and does not
necessarily indicate the presence of any security vulnerabilities.

1626.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1626.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1626.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1626.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1626.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 137 seconds.

discover your network architecture.

1639.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
1639.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
1639.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
1639.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.

1641.Name: Portable SDK for UPnP Devices (libupnp) < 1.6.18 Multiple Stack-based Buffer Overflows RCE
1641.Synopsis:
A network service running on the remote host is affected by multiple
remote code execution vulnerabilities.
1641.Description:
According to its banner, the version of Portable SDK for UPnP Devices
(libupnp) running on the remote host is prior to 1.6.18. It is,
therefore, affected by multiple remote code execution
vulnerabilities :

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1641.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.
1641.Plugin Output:
Server banner : Linux/2.6.22.10-0007-20100202, UPnP/1.0, Portable SDK for UPnP devices/1.6.2
  Source: UDP
  Installed version : 1.6.2
  Fixed version : 1.6.18

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the DeviceType URN. An unauthenticated,
    remote attacker can exploit this, via a specially
    crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary code.
    (CVE-2012-5958)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to two colons. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit this, via a
    specially crafted SSDP request, to execute arbitrary
    code. (CVE-2012-5959)

  - A stack-based buffer overflow condition exists in the
    unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c when handling Simple Service
    Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests that is triggered
    while copying the UDN prior to the '::upnp:rootdevice'
    string. An unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit
    this, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5960)

  - Multiple stack-based buffer overflow conditions exist in
    the unique_service_name() function within file
    ssdp/ssdp_server.c due to improper validation of the
    UDN, DeviceType, and ServiceType fields when parsing
    Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP) requests. An
    unauthenticated, remote attacker can exploit these
    issues, via a specially crafted SSDP request, to execute
    arbitrary code. (CVE-2012-5961, CVE-2012-5962,
    CVE-2012-5963, CVE-2012-5964, CVE-2012-5965)
1647.Solution:
Upgrade to libupnp version 1.6.18 or later. If libupnp is used as a
third party library by a different application, contact the vendor of
that application for a fix.

1695.Name: ICMP Timestamp Request Remote Date Disclosure
1695.Synopsis: It is possible to determine the exact time set on the remote host.
1695.Description:
The remote host answers to an ICMP timestamp request.  This allows an
attacker to know the date that is set on the targeted machine, which
may assist an unauthenticated, remote attacker in defeating time-based
authentication protocols.

Timestamps returned from machines running Windows Vista / 7 / 2008 /
2008 R2 are deliberately incorrect, but usually within 1000 seconds of
the actual system time.
1695.Solution:
Filter out the ICMP timestamp requests (13), and the outgoing ICMP
timestamp replies (14).
1695.Plugin Output: The difference between the local and remote clocks is 4950 seconds.

1697.Name: Open Port Re-check
1697.Synopsis: Previously open ports are now closed.
1697.Description:
One of several ports that were previously open are now closed or
unresponsive.

There are several possible reasons for this :

  - The scan may have caused a service to freeze or stop
    running.

  - An administrator may have stopped a particular service
    during the scanning process.

This might be an availability problem related to the following :

  - A network outage has been experienced during the scan,
    and the remote network cannot be reached anymore by the
    scanner.

  - This scanner may has been blacklisted by the system
    administrator or by an automatic intrusion detection /
    prevention system that detected the scan.

  - The remote host is now down, either because a user
    turned it off during the scan or because a select denial
    of service was effective.

In any case, the audit of the remote host might be incomplete and may
need to be done again.
1697.Plugin Output: Port 554 was detected as being open but is now closed

The remote device answered an SSDP M-SEARCH request. Therefore, it
supports 'Universal Plug and Play' (UPnP). This protocol provides

for home networks. An attacker could potentially leverage this to
discover your network architecture.

1710.Name: IP Forwarding Enabled
1710.Synopsis: The remote host has IP forwarding enabled.
1710.Description:
The remote host has IP forwarding enabled. An attacker can exploit
this to route packets through the host and potentially bypass some
firewalls / routers / NAC filtering.

Unless the remote host is a router, it is recommended that you disable
IP forwarding.
1710.Solution:
On Linux, you can disable IP forwarding by doing :

echo 0 > /proc/sys/net/ipv4/ip_forward

On Windows, set the key 'IPEnableRouter' to 0 under

HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters

On Mac OS X, you can disable IP forwarding by executing the command :

sysctl -w net.inet.ip.forwarding=0

For other systems, check with your vendor.
